ledge sections don't align perfectly with the heading titles, but that's expected. I'm identifying around five main content areas that need to be organized: the initial explanation, what's being created, the Form generation details, and the property addition rules with their corresponding code implementation. Looking at the V3 source structure, there are only 2 h2-level headings (marked with dashes in RST), but the knowledge file has 5 sections—which suggests the content has been split deeper into h3 and h4 levels. That's a reasonable expansion, though it does mean the section breakdown goes beyond just the top-level structure.\n\nNow I'm checking the fabrication analysis more carefully. The knowledge section on property addition rules matches what's in the source—both the rules about table-corresponding and non-corresponding properties are confirmed. The note about Entities being Forms with 1-to-1 correspondence to tables is also there in the source, just formatted differently (RST note directive versus markdown blockquote).\n\nMoving to the next section, the addition procedure steps are accurate too—adding properties with member variables, setters, and getters to the Form, then updating the Map-argument constructor with value-setting logic for those new properties. The source confirms both steps.\n\nSo far the knowledge file is holding up well. I'm starting to spot some actual discrepancies though—there's a section title mismatch in s2 where the index entry doesn't quite align with what's actually in the source. Looking back at the source table more carefully, SystemAccountEntity and UgroupSystemAccountEntity don't actually appear in the file list—they're only mentioned in the code example in s5, so the hints for s2 are fine. The main issue I'm finding is the section title mismatch where s2's index label says \"本項で説明する内容\" but the actual content is the file table, which could confuse an AI looking for that specific section. I'm identifying the missing PascalCase c